1. Checking the vuln service is running
- systemctl list-units --type=service | grep -i ftp
Or listen to the port:
- ss -tulpn | grep :21

If found, stop and disable it:
sudo systemctl stop vsftpd
sudo systemctl disable vsftpd


How to harden FTP (if required)
vsftpd hardening (/etc/vsftpd.conf)
anonymous_enable=NO
local_enable=YES
write_enable=NO
chroot_local_user=YES
allow_writeable_chroot=NO
ssl_enable=YES

Then Restart the service:
sudo systemctl restart vsftpd

What this does:
Security controls
Disable anonymous login
Use FTPS (TLS encryption)
Chroot users
Restrict write access
Firewall restrict port 21

For TELNET
systemctl status telnet.socket
ss -tulpn | grep :23

Disable it with 
sudo systemctl stop telnet.socket
sudo systemctl disable telnet.socket

rlogin / rsh (VERY dangerous)
systemctl list-units --type=service | grep -E 'rlogin|rsh|rexec'
ss -tulpn | grep -E ':512|:513|:514'

How to disable it
sudo systemctl stop rsh.socket rlogin.socket rexec.socket
sudo systemctl disable rsh.socket rlogin.socket rexec.socket

SSH Hardening (Replacement Best Practice)
/etc/ssh/sshd_config
PermitRootLogin no
PasswordAuthentication no
PubkeyAuthentication yes
MaxAuthTries 3
AllowUsers youruser

